\section{Writing the ProgSnap2 dataset}

The main export function walks the commit history, builds the
CSV tables, extracts code states, and packages everything into
a zip file.

The algorithm has three phases:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Walk commits to build the event rows, collect
  unique code state tree hashes, and accumulate I/O
  resource files.
\item Extract each unique code state into a temporary directory.
\item Write the zip file with [[DatasetMetadata.csv]],
  [[MainTable.csv]], [[CodeStates/]], and [[Resources/]]
  entries.
\end{enumerate}

We separate these phases because code state extraction requires
I/O to a temporary directory, and we want to minimise the
lifetime of that temporary data.

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def do_export_progsnap2(repo, output_path,
                        filter_learnlog_flag=True):
    """Export the learnlog repository as a ProgSnap2 zip.

    Creates a zip file at ``output_path`` containing
    ``DatasetMetadata.csv``, ``MainTable.csv``, a
    ``CodeStates/`` directory with source file snapshots,
    and a ``Resources/`` directory with I/O text files.
    """
    <<collect events and code states>>
    <<write progsnap2 zip file>>
@

\subsection{Collecting events}

We walk commits in chronological order, parsing each commit
message into run blocks.
For each commit we determine the code state and generate events:
a [[File.Edit]] event when the tree hash changes from the
previous commit, and a [[Run.Program]] event for each run block.

The [[Order]] column provides a global sequence number across
all events, scoped per subject (the [[EventOrderScope]] metadata
field).
Since learnlog records one student at a time, a single counter
suffices.

<<collect events and code states>>=
commits = get_commits(repo)
tag_map = get_tag_map(repo)
seen_trees = {}
events = []
resource_files = []
order = 0
prev_tree = None

for commit in commits:
    commit_hash = commit["hash"]
    commit_tags = ";".join(
        tag_map.get(commit_hash, [])
    )

    <<get subject and code state for commit>>
    <<optionally emit File.Edit event>>
    <<emit Run.Program events>>
@

We extract the author name as [[SubjectID]], since each learnlog
repository belongs to one student.
For timestamps, we use both [[ServerTimestamp]] and
[[ClientTimestamp]] set to the same value because learnlog
timestamps come from the local clock.

<<get subject and code state for commit>>=
author_result = repo.git(
    "log", "-1", "--format=%an", commit_hash,
)
subject_id = author_result.stdout.strip()

code_state_id, current_tree = get_code_state_id(
    repo, commit_hash, seen_trees,
)
@

A [[File.Edit]] event signals that the student changed their
source code.
We emit one whenever the current tree hash differs from the
previous commit's tree hash.
The initial commit also gets a [[File.Edit]] because writing
code for the first time is an edit from nothing---and
[[prev_tree]] starts as [[None]], which never equals a real
tree hash.

<<optionally emit File.Edit event>>=
if current_tree != prev_tree:
    order += 1
    events.append({
        "EventType": "File.Edit",
        "EventID": order,
        "Order": order,
        "SubjectID": subject_id,
        "CodeStateID": code_state_id,
        "ParentEventID": "",
        "ServerTimestamp": commit["date"],
        "ClientTimestamp": commit["date"],
        "ProgramResult": "",
        "X-ExitCode": "",
        "X-Script": "",
        "X-Arguments": "",
        "X-ExceptionType": "",
        "X-ExceptionMessage": "",
        "ProgramOutput": "",
        "ProgramInput": "",
        "X-Tag": commit_tags,
        "X-CommitHash": commit_hash,
    })
@

For each run block we emit a [[Run.Program]] event with the
parsed metadata.
When [[filter_learnlog_flag]] is set, we skip blocks whose
script is [[learnlog]] (the same filtering logic as
[[filter_learnlog_runs]], but at the parsed-block level
rather than raw text).

After emitting the [[Run.Program]] event, we generate
chunked I/O events for that run's captured output and input.
The spec recommends [[ParentEventID]] to link child events
to their parent (v8, \S4.3.6, lines~902--912), so each I/O
event references its parent [[Run.Program]]'s [[EventID]].
We save that ID in [[run_event_id]] before the order counter
advances past the I/O events.

<<emit Run.Program events>>=
body = repo.git(
    "log", "-1", "--format=%B", commit_hash,
).stdout.rstrip("\n")

runs = parse_commit_runs(body)
for run in runs:
    if filter_learnlog_flag \
            and run["script"] == "learnlog":
        continue

    order += 1
    run_event_id = order
    program_result = classify_run_result(run)
    exc_type, exc_msg = parse_exception_line(
        run["exception_info"]
    )

    timestamp = run["start_time"] or commit["date"]

    events.append({
        "EventType": "Run.Program",
        "EventID": order,
        "Order": order,
        "SubjectID": subject_id,
        "CodeStateID": code_state_id,
        "ParentEventID": "",
        "ServerTimestamp": timestamp,
        "ClientTimestamp": timestamp,
        "ProgramResult": program_result,
        "X-ExitCode": run["exit_code"] or "",
        "X-Script": run["script"] or "",
        "X-Arguments": run["arguments"] or "",
        "X-ExceptionType": exc_type or "",
        "X-ExceptionMessage": exc_msg or "",
        "ProgramOutput": "",
        "ProgramInput": "",
        "X-Tag": commit_tags,
        "X-CommitHash": commit_hash,
    })

    <<emit I/O events for run>>

prev_tree = current_tree
@

The ProgSnap2 spec defines [[ProgramInput]] and
[[ProgramOutput]] as URL-typed columns that reference files
in the [[Resources/]] directory (v8, \S4.4.2,
lines~1224--1261).
Each I/O chunk is written to a separate file named
[[io_{EventID}.txt]] under [[Resources/]], and the CSV
cell contains the relative path to that file.
Using the standard columns rather than custom inline
ones ensures that generic ProgSnap2 analysis tools can
read the I/O data without special handling---custom
[[X-]] columns are ignored by tools that do not
explicitly support them.

We use custom event types [[X-Run.Output]] and
[[X-Run.Input]] rather than embedding all I/O in the
[[Run.Program]] row because interactive programs interleave
output and input---a single column cannot represent the
conversational structure (prompt, response, more output,
etc.).
Timestamps are left empty because learnlog does not record
per-line timing; only the run-level timestamps are
available.

<<emit I/O events for run>>=
io_chunks = chunk_io_log(run["io_log"])
for evt_type, text in io_chunks:
    order += 1
    io_event = {
        "EventType": evt_type,
        "EventID": order,
        "Order": order,
        "SubjectID": subject_id,
        "CodeStateID": code_state_id,
        "ParentEventID": run_event_id,
        "ServerTimestamp": "",
        "ClientTimestamp": "",
        "ProgramResult": "",
        "X-ExitCode": "",
        "X-Script": "",
        "X-Arguments": "",
        "X-ExceptionType": "",
        "X-ExceptionMessage": "",
        "ProgramOutput": "",
        "ProgramInput": "",
        "X-Tag": commit_tags,
        "X-CommitHash": commit_hash,
    }
    resource_path = f"Resources/io_{order}.txt"
    if evt_type == "X-Run.Output":
        io_event["ProgramOutput"] = resource_path
    else:
        io_event["ProgramInput"] = resource_path
    resource_files.append((resource_path, text))
    events.append(io_event)
@

\subsection{Writing the zip file}

We build the zip in a temporary directory, extracting code
states into numbered subdirectories.
The [[DatasetMetadata.csv]] and [[MainTable.csv]] are written
as in-memory strings and added to the zip directly.

<<write progsnap2 zip file>>=
with tempfile.TemporaryDirectory(
    prefix="learnlog-ps2-"
) as tmpdir:
    tmppath = pathlib.Path(tmpdir)

    <<extract code states to temp directory>>
    <<build metadata csv string>>
    <<build main table csv string>>
    <<assemble zip file>>
@

We need a reverse mapping from tree hashes to commit hashes so
we can call [[extract_code_state]] with a concrete commit.
Multiple commits may share the same tree hash; we only need one
representative commit per tree, so we keep the first one seen.

<<extract code states to temp directory>>=
states_dir = tmppath / "CodeStates"
states_dir.mkdir()
tree_to_commit = {}
for commit in commits:
    tree_result = repo.git(
        "rev-parse", f"{commit['hash']}^{{tree}}"
    )
    tree_hash = tree_result.stdout.strip()
    if tree_hash not in tree_to_commit:
        tree_to_commit[tree_hash] = commit["hash"]

for tree_hash, state_id in seen_trees.items():
    commit_hash = tree_to_commit[tree_hash]
    state_subdir = states_dir / str(state_id)
    extract_code_state(repo, commit_hash, state_subdir)
@

The metadata CSV has two columns: [[Property]] and [[Value]].
We declare version~8, consistent event ordering scoped per
subject, and directory-based code state representation.

<<build metadata csv string>>=
metadata_buf = io.StringIO()
meta_writer = csv.writer(metadata_buf)
meta_writer.writerow(["Property", "Value"])
meta_writer.writerow(["Version", PROGSNAP2_VERSION])
meta_writer.writerow([
    "IsEventOrderingConsistent", "true"
])
meta_writer.writerow([
    "EventOrderScope", "Restricted"
])
meta_writer.writerow([
    "EventOrderScopeColumns", "SubjectID"
])
meta_writer.writerow([
    "CodeStateRepresentation", "Directory"
])
metadata_csv = metadata_buf.getvalue()
@

The main table includes the standard ProgSnap2 columns,
[[ParentEventID]] for linking I/O child events to their
parent [[Run.Program]] (v8, \S4.3.6, lines~902--912),
the standard [[ProgramOutput]] and [[ProgramInput]] columns
referencing files in [[Resources/]], and custom [[X-]]
columns for Python-specific metadata.
The [[X-Tag]] column carries any Git tags that point at
the commit that produced the event, semicolon-delimited
when a commit has multiple tags.
This lets analysis tools segment the dataset by lab session
or other user-defined milestones.
The [[X-CommitHash]] column records the full Git commit hash
that produced each event, enabling tools to filter events by
commit range even after the dataset has been exported to a
zip file.

<<build main table csv string>>=
main_columns = [
    "EventType", "EventID", "Order",
    "SubjectID", "CodeStateID",
    "ParentEventID",
    "ServerTimestamp", "ClientTimestamp",
    "ProgramResult",
    "X-ExitCode", "X-Script", "X-Arguments",
    "X-ExceptionType", "X-ExceptionMessage",
    "ProgramOutput",
    "ProgramInput",
    "X-Tag",
    "X-CommitHash",
]
main_buf = io.StringIO()
main_writer = csv.DictWriter(
    main_buf, fieldnames=main_columns
)
main_writer.writeheader()
for event in events:
    main_writer.writerow(event)
main_csv = main_buf.getvalue()
@

We write CSVs from in-memory strings rather than temporary files
to avoid extra I/O, and iterate subdirectories in sorted order
so that repeated exports of the same data produce
byte-identical archives---useful for checksumming and caching.
Resource files are likewise written from in-memory strings
collected during event generation; they are already ordered
by [[EventID]], so no additional sorting is needed.

<<assemble zip file>>=
with zipfile.ZipFile(
    str(output_path), "w",
    compression=zipfile.ZIP_DEFLATED,
) as zf:
    zf.writestr("DatasetMetadata.csv", metadata_csv)
    zf.writestr("MainTable.csv", main_csv)

    for state_subdir in sorted(states_dir.iterdir()):
        for fpath in sorted(state_subdir.rglob("*")):
            if fpath.is_file():
                arcname = (
                    "CodeStates/"
                    + state_subdir.name
                    + "/"
                    + str(
                        fpath.relative_to(state_subdir)
                    )
                )
                zf.write(str(fpath), arcname)

    for arcname, text in resource_files:
        zf.writestr(arcname, text)
@

