\section{Reading a ProgSnap2 dataset}
\label{sec:read-progsnap2}

The export pipeline writes ProgSnap2 datasets; the analysis
pipeline needs to read them back.
Rather than coupling the analyser to the internal export
data structures, we read from the standard zip format.
This means the analyser works equally well on datasets
exported by learnlog and on datasets produced by other
tools that follow the ProgSnap2 specification.

The reader returns a dict with four keys:
\begin{description}
\item[[[metadata]]] The [[DatasetMetadata.csv]] key--value
  pairs as a dict.
\item[[[events]]] The [[MainTable.csv]] rows as a list of
  dicts, preserving the CSV column names as keys.
\item[[[code_states]]] A nested dict mapping each
  [[CodeStateID]] to a dict of
  \{filename: file content\} pairs.
\item[[[resources]]] A dict mapping resource paths
  (e.g.\ [[Resources/io_3.txt]]) to their text content.
\end{description}

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def read_progsnap2(source):
    """Read a ProgSnap2 dataset from a zip file.

    ``source`` may be a file path (string or ``Path``) or
    a file-like object (e.g. ``BytesIO``).

    Returns a dict with keys ``metadata``, ``events``,
    ``code_states``, and ``resources``.
    """
    with zipfile.ZipFile(source, "r") as zf:
        <<read metadata csv>>
        <<read main table csv>>
        <<read code states from zip>>
        <<read resource files from zip>>

    return {
        "metadata": metadata,
        "events": events,
        "code_states": code_states,
        "resources": resources,
    }
@

The metadata CSV has two columns ([[Property]] and [[Value]]);
we flatten it into a simple dict.

<<read metadata csv>>=
meta_text = zf.read(
    "DatasetMetadata.csv"
).decode("utf-8")
reader = csv.DictReader(io.StringIO(meta_text))
metadata = {
    row["Property"]: row["Value"]
    for row in reader
}
@

The main table is the heart of the dataset---one row per event.
We preserve all columns as strings, matching the CSV
representation.

<<read main table csv>>=
main_text = zf.read(
    "MainTable.csv"
).decode("utf-8")
reader = csv.DictReader(io.StringIO(main_text))
events = list(reader)
@

Code states live under [[CodeStates/{id}/]] in the zip.
We read each file's content as a string, grouping by state ID.
Binary files are skipped---ProgSnap2 is designed for source
code, and our code states contain only text files.

<<read code states from zip>>=
code_states = {}
for name in zf.namelist():
    if not name.startswith("CodeStates/"):
        continue
    parts = name[len("CodeStates/"):].split("/", 1)
    if len(parts) < 2 or not parts[1]:
        continue
    state_id = parts[0]
    filename = parts[1]
    if state_id not in code_states:
        code_states[state_id] = {}
    try:
        code_states[state_id][filename] = (
            zf.read(name).decode("utf-8")
        )
    except UnicodeDecodeError:
        pass
@

Resource files (I/O text) live under [[Resources/]].

<<read resource files from zip>>=
resources = {}
for name in zf.namelist():
    if not name.startswith("Resources/"):
        continue
    resources[name] = (
        zf.read(name).decode("utf-8")
    )
@

We verify the reader by round-tripping through the export
pipeline: export a repository, then read it back and check
that the structure is intact.

