\section{Grouping events into edit--run pairs}
\label{sec:group-pairs}

An analysis of student behaviour focuses on the
\emph{edit--run cycle}: the student changes their code,
runs the program, observes the result, and edits again.
To present this cycle we group the flat event list into
pairs of (edit, run) within each student and tag.

The grouping algorithm walks events in [[Order]] for each
[[SubjectID]].
A [[File.Edit]] event opens a new pair; the next
[[Run.Program]] event (with its I/O children) closes it.
Edge cases: an edit with no following run gets
[[run=None]], and a re-run without a preceding edit gets
[[edit=None]].

We group by [[X-Tag]] because tags represent logical
milestones (lab sessions, exercises) that the instructor
defined.
When a commit has multiple Git tags, the exporter stores them
as a semicolon-delimited [[X-Tag]] value; the analyser splits
that field back into individual tags so the same pair appears
under each relevant heading.
Events with an empty tag are grouped under the key [[""]].

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def _iter_event_tags(tag_value):
    """Yield individual tags from a semicolon-delimited value."""
    tags = [tag for tag in (tag_value or "").split(";") if tag]
    return tags or [""]
@

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def group_edit_run_pairs(events):
    """Group events into edit--run pairs per subject and tag.

    Returns a nested dict::

        {subject_id: {tag: [pair, ...]}}

    where each pair is a dict with keys ``edit``, ``run``,
    ``io``, and ``code_state_id``.
    """
    <<sort events by subject and order>>
    <<walk events to form pairs>>
    return grouped
@

We first partition events by [[SubjectID]], sorting each
partition by [[Order]] to ensure chronological processing.

<<sort events by subject and order>>=
by_subject = {}
for event in events:
    sid = event["SubjectID"]
    if sid not in by_subject:
        by_subject[sid] = []
    by_subject[sid].append(event)

for sid in by_subject:
    by_subject[sid].sort(key=lambda e: int(e["Order"]))
@

For each subject we walk the sorted events.
A [[File.Edit]] starts a new pair accumulator.
A [[Run.Program]] completes the current pair.
I/O events ([[X-Run.Output]], [[X-Run.Input]]) are attached
to the most recent [[Run.Program]] via [[ParentEventID]].
When a [[Run.Program]] appears without a preceding
[[File.Edit]], we create a pair with [[edit=None]]---this
happens when the student re-runs without editing.

<<walk events to form pairs>>=
grouped = {}
for sid, subj_events in by_subject.items():
    grouped[sid] = {}
    current_edit = None
    current_tag = ""
    pairs_by_tag = {}
    run_io_map = {}

    for event in subj_events:
        etype = event["EventType"]
        tag = event.get("X-Tag", "") or ""

        if etype == "File.Edit":
            <<flush pending edit without run>>
            current_edit = event
            current_tag = tag
        elif etype == "Run.Program":
            <<create pair from edit and run>>
        elif etype in (
            "X-Run.Output", "X-Run.Input"
        ):
            <<attach I/O to parent run>>

    <<flush final pending edit>>

    grouped[sid] = pairs_by_tag
@

If a new [[File.Edit]] arrives while a previous edit has
no run yet, we flush the orphan edit as a pair with
[[run=None]].

<<flush pending edit without run>>=
if current_edit is not None:
    pair = {
        "edit": current_edit,
        "run": None,
        "io": [],
        "code_state_id": (
            current_edit["CodeStateID"]
        ),
    }
    for t in _iter_event_tags(current_tag):
        if t not in pairs_by_tag:
            pairs_by_tag[t] = []
        pairs_by_tag[t].append(pair)
    current_edit = None
@

When a [[Run.Program]] arrives we pair it with the pending
edit (or [[None]] if there was no edit).
We record the pair index in [[run_io_map]] so that
subsequent I/O events can find their parent pair.

<<create pair from edit and run>>=
tag_value = tag if current_edit is None else current_tag
pair = {
    "edit": current_edit,
    "run": event,
    "io": [],
    "code_state_id": event["CodeStateID"],
}
for t in _iter_event_tags(tag_value):
    if t not in pairs_by_tag:
        pairs_by_tag[t] = []
    pairs_by_tag[t].append(pair)
run_io_map[event["EventID"]] = pair
current_edit = None
@

I/O events reference their parent [[Run.Program]] via
[[ParentEventID]].
We look up the parent pair and append the I/O event.

<<attach I/O to parent run>>=
parent_id = event.get("ParentEventID", "")
if parent_id in run_io_map:
    run_io_map[parent_id]["io"].append(event)
@

At the end of the event stream, a trailing edit with no
run is flushed.

<<flush final pending edit>>=
if current_edit is not None:
    pair = {
        "edit": current_edit,
        "run": None,
        "io": [],
        "code_state_id": (
            current_edit["CodeStateID"]
        ),
    }
    for t in _iter_event_tags(current_tag):
        if t not in pairs_by_tag:
            pairs_by_tag[t] = []
        pairs_by_tag[t].append(pair)
@

