\section{\LaTeX{} analysis output}
\label{sec:latex-analysis}

The analysis generates \LaTeX{} source that presents
the student's edit--run cycle.
The output uses [[minted]] for syntax-highlighted code
listings and [[paracol]] for the side-by-side mode.
We generate a fragment by default (sections and
subsections that the user [[\\input]]s into their own
document) and optionally a standalone document.

\subsection{Main generation function}

The entry point takes the dataset (from
[[read_progsnap2]]), the grouped pairs (from
[[group_edit_run_pairs]]), and mode flags.
It returns a string of \LaTeX{} source.

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def generate_analysis_latex(
    dataset, grouped,
    side_by_side=False, standalone=False,
):
    """Generate LaTeX analysis of edit--run pairs.

    Returns a string of LaTeX source code.  When
    ``standalone`` is true, the output is a complete
    document; otherwise it is a fragment suitable for
    ``\\input{}``.
    """
    lines = []

    if standalone:
        <<emit standalone preamble>>

    for subject_id in sorted(grouped.keys()):
        <<emit subject section>>

    if standalone:
        lines.append("\\end{document}")

    return "\n".join(lines) + "\n"
@

<<emit standalone preamble>>=
lines.append("\\documentclass{article}")
lines.append("\\usepackage{minted}")
lines.append("\\usepackage{paracol}")
lines.append("\\begin{document}")
lines.append("")
@

\subsection{Subject and tag sections}

Each student gets a [[\\section]] and each tag a
[[\\subsection]].
When all events for a subject are untagged (single
empty-string key), we skip the [[\\subsection]] level
to avoid a pointless heading.

<<emit subject section>>=
lines.append(
    f"\\section{{{_latex_escape(subject_id)}}}"
)
lines.append("")
tags = grouped[subject_id]
only_untagged = (
    list(tags.keys()) == [""]
)

for tag in sorted(tags.keys()):
    pairs = tags[tag]
    if not only_untagged:
        tag_label = tag if tag else "(untagged)"
        lines.append(
            "\\subsection{"
            f"{_latex_escape(tag_label)}"
            "}"
        )
        lines.append("")

    if side_by_side:
        <<emit pairs side by side>>
    else:
        <<emit pairs sequentially>>
@

\subsection{Sequential mode}

In the default mode, each edit--run pair is listed
top to bottom.
The edit shows a unified diff (or the full file for
the first edit), and the run shows the script, result,
and captured I/O.

<<emit pairs sequentially>>=
prev_pair = None
for i, pair in enumerate(pairs, 1):
    edit_tex = format_edit_latex(
        pair, prev_pair,
        dataset["code_states"],
    )
    if edit_tex:
        lines.append(
            f"\\paragraph{{Edit {i}}}"
        )
        lines.append(edit_tex)
        lines.append("")

    run_tex = format_run_latex(
        pair, dataset["resources"],
    )
    if run_tex:
        lines.append(
            f"\\paragraph{{Run {i}}}"
        )
        lines.append(run_tex)
        lines.append("")

    prev_pair = pair
@

\subsection{Side-by-side mode}

The side-by-side mode uses [[paracol]] to show the
causal chain: the left column contains the previous
run result (what the student observed), the right
column contains the current edit and run (what the
student did in response).
For pair~$N$, the left column shows pair~$N{-}1$'s
run result; the right column shows pair~$N$'s edit
and run.
The first pair has an empty left column.

<<emit pairs side by side>>=
lines.append("\\begin{paracol}{2}")
prev_pair = None
for i, pair in enumerate(pairs, 1):
    lines.append("\\switchcolumn[0]")
    if prev_pair is not None:
        prev_run = format_run_latex(
            prev_pair, dataset["resources"],
        )
        if prev_run:
            lines.append(
                "\\paragraph{"
                f"Run {i - 1} result"
                "}"
            )
            lines.append(prev_run)
    lines.append("")

    lines.append("\\switchcolumn[1]")
    edit_tex = format_edit_latex(
        pair, prev_pair,
        dataset["code_states"],
    )
    if edit_tex:
        lines.append(
            f"\\paragraph{{Edit {i}}}"
        )
        lines.append(edit_tex)
        lines.append("")

    run_tex = format_run_latex(
        pair, dataset["resources"],
    )
    if run_tex:
        lines.append(
            f"\\paragraph{{Run {i}}}"
        )
        lines.append(run_tex)
        lines.append("")

    prev_pair = pair
lines.append("\\end{paracol}")
lines.append("")
@

\subsection{Formatting an edit}

An edit is shown as a unified diff between the previous
and current code states.
For the first edit (no previous state), we show the full
file content instead---the student wrote this code from
scratch.
If the pair has no edit ([[edit=None]], a re-run), we
return an empty string.

We use [[difflib.unified_diff]] to compute the diff.
When multiple files changed, we concatenate the diffs
for each file.

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def format_edit_latex(pair, prev_pair, code_states):
    """Format the edit part of a pair as LaTeX.

    Returns a string with a ``minted`` block showing
    either a unified diff or the full file content.
    Returns an empty string if there is no edit.
    """
    if pair["edit"] is None:
        return ""

    state_id = pair["code_state_id"]
    current = code_states.get(state_id, {})

    prev_state_id = (
        prev_pair["code_state_id"]
        if prev_pair is not None
        else None
    )
    previous = (
        code_states.get(prev_state_id, {})
        if prev_state_id is not None
        else {}
    )

    if not previous:
        <<format first edit as full file>>
    else:
        <<format edit as unified diff>>
@

When there is no previous state, we show each file
in its entirety.
To keep the filename visible in the rendered document, we emit
an explicit label rather than a LaTeX comment.

<<format first edit as full file>>=
parts = []
for filename in sorted(current.keys()):
    content = current[filename]
    parts.append(
        "\\textbf{File: "
        f"\\texttt{{{_latex_escape(filename)}}}"
        "}"
    )
    parts.append("")
    parts.append("\\begin{minted}{python}")
    parts.append(content.rstrip())
    parts.append("\\end{minted}")
return "\n".join(parts)
@

For subsequent edits, we compute a unified diff per
file.
Files that did not change are skipped.
New files show as additions; deleted files as removals.

<<format edit as unified diff>>=
all_files = sorted(
    set(list(previous.keys())
        + list(current.keys()))
)
parts = []
for filename in all_files:
    old = previous.get(filename, "")
    new = current.get(filename, "")
    if old == new:
        continue
    diff_lines = list(difflib.unified_diff(
        old.splitlines(keepends=True),
        new.splitlines(keepends=True),
        fromfile=f"a/{filename}",
        tofile=f"b/{filename}",
    ))
    if diff_lines:
        parts.append("\\begin{minted}{diff}")
        parts.append(
            "".join(diff_lines).rstrip()
        )
        parts.append("\\end{minted}")
if not parts:
    return ""
return "\n".join(parts)
@

\subsection{Formatting a run}

A run shows the script name, result classification,
and captured I/O.
If the pair has no run ([[run=None]]), we return an
empty string.

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def format_run_latex(pair, resources):
    """Format the run part of a pair as LaTeX.

    Returns a string with script info and I/O in a
    ``minted`` block.  Returns empty string if no run.
    """
    if pair["run"] is None:
        return ""

    run = pair["run"]
    parts = []

    script = run.get("X-Script", "")
    result = run.get("ProgramResult", "")
    exit_code = run.get("X-ExitCode", "")

    info_parts = []
    if script:
        info_parts.append(
            f"Script: \\texttt{{{_latex_escape(script)}}}"
        )
    if result:
        info_parts.append(f"Result: {result}")
    if exit_code:
        info_parts.append(
            f"Exit code: {exit_code}"
        )
    if info_parts:
        parts.append(" \\\\\n".join(info_parts))
        parts.append("")

    <<format exception info>>

    io_text = format_io_latex(
        pair["io"], resources,
    )
    if io_text:
        parts.append("\\begin{minted}{text}")
        parts.append(io_text)
        parts.append("\\end{minted}")

    return "\n".join(parts)
@

If the run produced an exception, we show it in its
own [[minted]] block so the reader can see what error
the student encountered.

<<format exception info>>=
exc_type = run.get("X-ExceptionType", "")
exc_msg = run.get("X-ExceptionMessage", "")
if exc_type:
    exc_str = exc_type
    if exc_msg:
        exc_str += f": {exc_msg}"
    parts.append("\\begin{minted}{pytb}")
    parts.append(exc_str)
    parts.append("\\end{minted}")
    parts.append("")
@

\subsection{Formatting I/O}

I/O events are stored as resource files in the zip.
We read each resource and concatenate them, prefixing
input lines with [[>~]] so the reader can distinguish
what the student typed from what the program printed.

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def format_io_latex(io_events, resources):
    """Format I/O events as plain text for minted.

    Input lines are prefixed with ``> `` to distinguish
    them from program output.
    Returns an empty string if there are no I/O events.
    """
    if not io_events:
        return ""

    parts = []
    for event in io_events:
        etype = event["EventType"]
        res_path = (
            event.get("ProgramOutput", "")
            or event.get("ProgramInput", "")
        )
        text = resources.get(res_path, "")
        if etype == "X-Run.Input":
            for line in text.split("\n"):
                parts.append(f"> {line}")
        else:
            parts.append(text)

    return "\n".join(parts).rstrip()
@

\subsection{\LaTeX{} escaping}

We need a minimal escaping function for text that
appears in \LaTeX{} commands (section titles, script
names).
Full escaping of all special characters is needed
to prevent compilation errors from underscores, ampersands,
and similar characters in student names or filenames.
We escape one character at a time so replacement text is not
re-escaped by later substitutions.

<<progsnap2 functions>>=
def _latex_escape(text):
    """Escape LaTeX special characters in text."""
    replacements = {
        "\\": "\\textbackslash{}",
        "&": "\\&",
        "%": "\\%",
        "$": "\\$",
        "#": "\\#",
        "_": "\\_",
        "{": "\\{",
        "}": "\\}",
        "~": "\\textasciitilde{}",
        "^": "\\textasciicircum{}",
    }
    return "".join(
        replacements.get(char, char)
        for char in text
    )
@

